# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cwpp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:cwpp/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:cwpp/cloud-workload-protection-platform] A **cloud workload protection platform (CWPP)** is a computer security software aimed at securing (potentially virtual) computer machines.
[src:cwpp/cloud-workload-protection-platform] CWPPs are usually agent-based, meaning that a software agent is running permanently within the machine to be protected, collecting security-relevant data and events and sending those to a cloud-based service.
[src:cwpp/cloud-workload-protection-platform] The cloud-based service monitors all the machines under its supervision, derives alerts and notifies users about corresponding potential security threats.
[src:cwpp/cloud-workload-protection-platform] Gartner maintains a list of CWPP vendor-based solutions.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:cwpp/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] The endpoint security space has evolved during the 2010s away from limited antivirus software and into a more advanced, comprehensive defense.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] This includes next-generation antivirus, threat detection, investigation, and response, device management, data leak protection (DLP), and other considerations to face evolving threats.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] Endpoint security management is a software approach that helps to identify and manage the users' computer and data access over a corporate network.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] This allows the network administrator to restrict the use of sensitive data as well as certain website access to specific users, to maintain, and comply with the organization's policies and standards.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] The components involved in aligning the endpoint security management systems include a virtual private network (VPN) client, an operating system and an updated endpoint agent.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] Computer devices that are not in compliance with the organization's policy are provisioned with limited access to a virtual LAN.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] Encrypting data on endpoints, and removable storage devices help to protect against data leaks.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] Endpoint security systems operate on a client-server model, with the security program controlled by a centrally managed host server pinned with a client program that is installed on all the network drives.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] There is another model called software as a service (SaaS), where the security programs and the host server are maintained remotely by the merchant.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] In the payment card industry, the contribution from both the delivery models is that the server program verifies and authenticates the user login credentials and performs a device scan to check if it complies with designated corporate security standards prior to permitting network access.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] In addition to protecting an organization's endpoints from potential threats, endpoint security allows IT admins to monitor operation functions and data backup strategies.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] An endpoint protection platform (EPP) is a solution deployed on endpoint devices to prevent file-based malware attacks, detect malicious activity, and provide the investigation and remediation capabilities needed to respond to dynamic security incidents and alerts.
[src:cwpp/endpoint-security] Several vendors, like Microsoft Defender, CrowdStrike, and Absolute Security, produce systems converging EPP systems with endpoint detection and response (EDR) platforms – systems focused on threat detection, response, and unified monitoring.
[src:cwpp/runtime-application-self-protection] RASP can be integrated as a framework or module that runs in conjunction with a program's codes, libraries and system calls.
[src:cwpp/runtime-application-self-protection] The technology can also be implemented as a virtualization.
[src:cwpp/runtime-application-self-protection] RASP solutions can be deployed in two different ways: monitor or protection mode.
[src:cwpp/runtime-application-self-protection] In monitor mode, the RASP solution reports on web application attacks but does not block any attack.
[src:cwpp/runtime-application-self-protection] In protection mode, the RASP solution reports and blocks web application attacks.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:cwpp/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
